05670nam a22008295i 9789048544059DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485440597 a10.1515/97890485440592doi  a(DE-B1597)527192  a(OCoLC)1090494587  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a362.40943704aThe Politics of Disability in Interwar and Socialist Czechoslovakia :bSegregating in the Name of the Nation /ced. by Victoria Shmidt. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage and Memory Studies ;v700tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of Archives and Used Abbreviations -- tIntroduction. The Politics of Disability: Structure and Agency in Nation Building in Czechoslovakia -- tPart 1. Building the Czechoslovak Nation and Sacralizing Peoples' Health: The Vicissitudes of Disability Discourse during the Interwar Period -- tIntroduction -- t1. Establishing National Public Health in Interwar Czechoslovakia -- t2. The Discourse of Disability -- t3. Politics Concerning the Roma during the Interwar Period -- tPart 2. Postwar Institutionalization of Care for the Disabled: Toward a Universalized Discourse of "Defective Gypsies" -- tIntroduction -- t4. Special Education in Czechoslovakia between 1939 and 1989 -- t5. The Intersectionality of Disability and Race in Public and Professional Discourses about the Roma in Socialist Czechoslovakia -- t6. The Forced Sterilization of Roma Women between the 1970s and the 1980s -- tConclusions -- tAbstracts in German and French -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnswering the question concerning what driving forces had led public health, welfare policy and education to operate as agents and structures of segregation is one of the core prerequisites for sustainable desegregation and historical justice. This book reexamines the politics of disability in interwar and socialist Czechoslovakia as embedded into nation building, recruited to legitimize diverse forms of structural violence against people with disabilities and ethnic minorities. The authors trace the intersectionality of ethnicity and disability, which proliferated across diverse realms of public life, positioning the continuities and ruptures of interrogating propaganda and racial science during the interwar and post-war periods as establishing and reinforcing the border between a healthy Czech majority and a disabled Roma minority. Writing from their experience, the authors critically revise this border that remains observable but unapproachable until it operates as a part of constructing the authenticity of a nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aDisabilitieszCzechoslovakia. 4aContemporary Period. 4aHeritage Studies. 4aHistory. 4aModern Period. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aNation building, Disability, Racial science, Roma, Czechoslovakia.1 aHenschel, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPančocha, Karel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShmidt, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShmidt, Victoria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066152108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232